# âœ… **PART 10 â€” Alembic Migration Setup (Same as Laravel Migrations)**

## ğŸ“Œ Step 1 â€” Initialize Alembic

```
alembic init migrations
```

This creates:

```
migrations/
alembic.ini
```

---

## ğŸ“Œ Step 2 â€” Open `alembic.ini` and change database URL

Find:

```
sqlalchemy.url = sqlite:///./test.db
```

Change to:

```
sqlalchemy.url = mysql+pymysql://root:password@localhost:3306/todo_app
```

---

## ğŸ“Œ Step 3 â€” Update migrations/env.py

Find:

```python
target_metadata = None
```

Replace with:

```python
from app.database.connection import Base
from app.models.user import User

target_metadata = Base.metadata
```

âœ” Now Alembic knows your models
âœ” Same as Laravel reading migrations

---

# ğŸš€ Create First Migration (same as Laravel: php artisan make:migration)

```
alembic revision --autogenerate -m "create users table"
```

---

# ğŸš€ Apply Migration (same as Laravel: php artisan migrate)

```
alembic upgrade head
```

---

# ğŸš€ Update Migration (same as Laravel: modify table)

Example: You add a column in `User` model
Run again:

```
alembic revision --autogenerate -m "add new column"
alembic upgrade head
```

---

# âš¡ BONUS â€” Database Seeder (Laravel Seeder Equivalent)

Create file:

### ğŸ“Œ `app/database/seeder.py`

```python
from app.models.user import User
from app.database.connection import SessionLocal

def seed():
    db = SessionLocal()
    user = User(username="admin", email="admin@example.com")
    db.add(user)
    db.commit()
```

Run seeder:

```
python -c "from app.database.seeder import seed; seed()"
```

